          "body": "Verse 17 is the chapter's pastoral heart and its greatest irony. 'Behold, how happy is the man whom God reproves, so do not despise the discipline of the Almighty.' The beatitude formula (*esher*) is genuine — Proverbs 3:11-12 teaches the same, and Hebrews 12:5-6 will cite that text directly. The theology of divine discipline is real and true. God does wound and heal, inflict pain and give relief (5:18); the same hand that strikes is the hand that mends. But Eliphaz has made a fatal identification error: he has concluded that Job's suffering must be God's discipline for Job's sin, because that is the only category his retributive framework possesses. He has no slot for the righteous sufferer — no category for the man whom God Himself has called 'blameless and upright' (1:8) and yet has permitted to be stripped of everything. The true content of 5:17-18 — that God disciplines those He loves — will find its full expression in Hebrews 12 and the cross, where the wound and the healing belong to the same redemptive event. Eliphaz is right about the pattern; he is catastrophically wrong about Job."
