          "title": "The closing claim: 'we have investigated it, and so it is' (5:27)",
          "body": "Eliphaz closes with a collective assertion of verified wisdom: 'Behold this; we have investigated it, and so it is. Hear it, and know for yourself.' The verb *chaqar* (to investigate, search out, probe) is the same root as *cheqer* (unsearchable) in verse 9 — an unintentional self-contradiction. In verse 9 Eliphaz praised God for doing things that are *beyond investigation*; in verse 27 he claims to have *fully investigated* the application of those things to Job. The gap between those two claims is the gap between true theology and overconfident application. The entire speech illustrates what D. A. Carson calls 'the danger of correct doctrine used as a bludgeon' — Eliphaz has not falsified the doctrines he holds; he has overextended their application to a specific case God Himself has never explained to him. God's response in chapters 38-41 will not correct Eliphaz's doctrine of creation; it will demolish his claim to have 'investigated' what only God knows. The reader, holding the prologue, already knows what Eliphaz does not: Job's suffering has a cause that lies entirely outside the retributive framework Eliphaz has 'investigated.'"
